{"id":"2206","paper":{"title":{"text":"A Reverse Pinsker Inequality "},"authors":[{"name":"Berend, Daniel"},{"name":"HarremoÃ«s, Peter"},{"name":"Kontorovich, Aryeh"}],"abstr":{"text":"Pinsker's widely used inequality upper-bounds the total variation distance ${||P-Q||}_1$ in terms of the Kullback-Leibler divergence $D(P||Q)$. Although in general a bound in the reverse direction is impossible, in many applications the quantity of interest is actually $D^*(P,\\epsilon)$ --- defined, for an arbitrary fixed $P$, as the infimum of $D(P||Q)$ over all distributions $Q$ that are $\\epsilon$-far away from $P$ in total variation. We show that $D^*(P\\epsilon)\\le C_\\epsilon^2 + O(\\epsilon^3)$, where $C=C(P)=1/2$ for ``balanced`` distributions, thereby providing a kind of reverse Pinsker inequality. Some of the structural results obtained in the course of the proof may be of independent interest. An application to large deviations is given. arXiv:1206.6544 "},"body":{"text":""},"refs":[]},"file":{"jsonClass":"File","file":"/home/arnfred/Code/trailhead/resources/ita2013/2206"},"links":[{"id":"2760","weight":3},{"id":"2741","weight":22},{"id":"3180","weight":4},{"id":"67","weight":2},{"id":"1606","weight":11},{"id":"153","weight":2},{"id":"3037","weight":9},{"id":"93","weight":2},{"id":"436","weight":2},{"id":"3191","weight":7},{"id":"223","weight":6},{"id":"1547","weight":2},{"id":"2254","weight":11},{"id":"1278","weight":4},{"id":"2287","weight":2},{"id":"3200","weight":11},{"id":"3008","weight":2},{"id":"3083","weight":2},{"id":"2217","weight":23},{"id":"307","weight":3},{"id":"1430","weight":3},{"id":"3021","weight":20},{"id":"3199","weight":3},{"id":"813","weight":6},{"id":"2634","weight":4},{"id":"526","weight":10},{"id":"2442","weight":4},{"id":"3183","weight":2},{"id":"175","weight":2},{"id":"2763","weight":4},{"id":"2534","weight":3},{"id":"702","weight":4},{"id":"450","weight":2},{"id":"770","weight":11},{"id":"3165","weight":3},{"id":"1082","weight":16},{"id":"1889